# Pull Request Quality Standards

## PR Size Rules

### Maximum PR Size
- **Small**: < 200 lines changed - Preferred for most changes
- **Medium**: 200-500 lines changed - Requires additional review
- **Large**: 500+ lines changed - Must be broken down further

### When to Split PRs
- Multiple unrelated features
- Refactoring mixed with feature work
- Changes spanning multiple domains
- Complex changes requiring extensive testing

## Verification Requirements

### Automated Verification
- All existing tests must pass
- Code must pass linting and formatting checks
- Security scans must pass
- Build must succeed in CI environment

### Manual Verification
- Code review by at least one qualified reviewer
- Functional testing of changed features
- Regression testing of related functionality
- Performance impact assessment for significant changes

## Documentation Expectations

### PR Description Requirements
- Clear description of what changed
- Explanation of why changes were needed
- How changes were verified
- Any risks or concerns
- Rollback plan if applicable

### Code Documentation
- Update relevant docs for API changes
- Add inline comments for complex logic
- Update README if user-facing changes
- Document breaking changes clearly

## Review Checklist

### Code Quality
- [ ] Follows established code style
- [ ] Includes appropriate error handling
- [ ] Has meaningful variable/function names
- [ ] Maintains backward compatibility
- [ ] Includes necessary logging

### Testing
- [ ] Unit tests added/updated for new code
- [ ] Integration tests added for API changes
- [ ] Manual testing completed
- [ ] Edge cases considered

### Security
- [ ] No secrets or sensitive data exposed
- [ ] Input validation implemented
- [ ] Authentication/authorization checked
- [ ] Dependencies reviewed for vulnerabilities

### Documentation
- [ ] Code comments added where needed
- [ ] Documentation updated
- [ ] Breaking changes documented
- [ ] Migration guide provided if needed

## Approval Requirements

### Single Approver
- Small, low-risk changes
- Bug fixes with tests
- Documentation updates
- Non-functional changes

### Multiple Approvers
- API changes
- Security-related changes
- Database schema changes
- Infrastructure changes
- Changes to core business logic

### Lead/Architect Approval
- Architectural changes
- Major refactoring
- New technology adoption
- Changes affecting multiple systems